&gt; _&quot;... does invoke this method have the same effect as adding a piece of code like this directly to the method? ...&quot;_

More or less.&amp;nbsp; The _scope_ will be different, of course, and it&#39;s an extra call to the _stack_.\
This topic is typically covered in most _Java_ introductory tutorials.

&gt; _&quot;... I&#39;m try to implement a HashMap which rejects null key. When my map receive a null key, it will throw an IllegalArgumentException. ...&quot;_

You can _encapsulate_ the _HashMap_ class, and _override_ the _put_ method to evaluate a _null_ key _argument_.

Here is an example.

```java
class HashMapNonNull&lt;K, V&gt; extends HashMap&lt;K, V&gt; {
    @Override
    public V put(K key, V value) {
        if (key == null)
            throw new IllegalArgumentException(&quot;Key should not be null!&quot;);
        return super.put(key, value);
    }
}
```

And, here is an example usage.

```java
HashMapNonNull&lt;String, Integer&gt; map = new HashMapNonNull&lt;&gt;();
map.put(null, 1);
```

Output

```none
Exception in thread &quot;main&quot; java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Key should not be null!
	at Example$HashMapNonNull.put(Example.java:15)
	at Example.main(Example.java:8)
```

Additionally, you may want to _override_ the _putAll_ and _putIfAbscent_ methods.

```java
@Override
public void putAll(Map&lt;? extends K, ? extends V&gt; m) {
    for (K k : m.keySet())
        if (k == null)
            throw new IllegalArgumentException(&quot;Key should not be null!&quot;);
    super.putAll(m);
}
```

```java
@Override
public V putIfAbsent(K key, V value) {
    if (key == null)
        throw new IllegalArgumentException(&quot;Key should not be null!&quot;);
    return super.putIfAbsent(key, value);
}
```

