answers.body_markdown:
The instance name starting with prefix `my` indicates, that it is your own implementation.

### Imaginative assumption of given listener API
In the 3rd paragraph of section [4.4.2. Asynchronous and Multi-threaded: create](https://projectreactor.io/docs/core/release/reference/#producing.create) there might be the assumptive introduction:

&gt; Imagine that **you use a listener-based API**. It processes data by chunks and has two events: (1) a chunk of data is ready and (2) the processing is complete (terminal event), as represented in the `MyEventListener` interface:
&gt; ```
&gt; interface MyEventListener&lt;T&gt; {
&gt;    void onDataChunk(List&lt;T&gt; chunk);
&gt;    void processComplete();
&gt;}
&gt;```

I highlighted the assumption in bold. The docs assume for illustrative purposes that you have a _listener-based API_ already. That is:

1. a custom *event-processor* like `MyEventProcesso&lt;T&gt;` that implements a method `register(MyEventListener&lt;T&gt; listener)`
2. a custom *event-listener* that implements the interface given above 

### Example illustrates how to use Flux sink with your listener API
If you now want to use Flux to `create` a bridge to your event-listener-based API. With this method-call of `create` you will register a listener instance:
```
myEventProcessor.register(
  // your given event-listener that uses the sink
);
```
In the example the listener instance uses the `sink` to hand-over events of that chunk of data. So, the listener implementation bridges between your given API and the Flux&#39;s sink.

